Thousands of foreign nationals aboard the diamond princess are being evacuated after nearly two weeks stranded at Yokohama's big black terminal. In the face of the challenge posed by the new pneumonia, US Secretary of State Pompeo said on Monday (February 17) that he would do whatever it took to reduce the public's risk of the disease.

In the early hours of Feb. 17, two American chartered planes, ending in N716ck and N710ck, successfully landed on U.S. soil at 4:56 and 2:28, respectively. The 747s carry more than 300 American passengers and their families who volunteered to evacuate the diamond princess.

As the Pentagon revealed earlier, they will be under a 14-day enforced quarantine at Travis in California and Lackland Air Force Base in Texas.

But the journey home was not an easy one. On the way to the Tokyo International Airport flight, the U.S. was suddenly notified that 14 evacuated U.S. citizens had been diagnosed with new crown pneumonia in tests conducted two days earlier. In this case, the State Department decided to let the 14 cases and other passengers board the plane, and the 14 passengers were quarantined.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A bus carrying American passengers from a cruise ship on Feb. 16. Source: twitter

In addition, more than 40 American tourists who were diagnosed before Feb. 16 were detained in Japan. "They're not going anywhere, they're going to be in a Japanese hospital, " Anthony Fauci, the National Director of Allergy and Institute of Medical Science, told CBS

The diamond princess departed from Yokohama on January 20 and returned to Yokohama early on February 3. Since an 80-year-old man who stepped off the ship in Hong Kong, China, on January 25 was diagnosed on February 1, the ship has been in quarantine for two weeks since February 5, after returning early, 2,666 guests and 1,045 crew members are grounded until Feb. 19.

As of 16 February, 356 confirmed cases had been detected on board, of which at least 60 were United States citizens. According to the latest Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare News on the evening of February 17, the cruise ship 17,99 new confirmed infected COVID-19, of which 70 asymptomatic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 16, one of the chartered planes responsible for evacuating American passengers at the Tokyo International Airport. Source: CNN

"It's like a Hot Spot, " FAUCI told CBS's Face The Nation on Sunday, explaining why so many people were infected. "It's just so infectious. "

While the United States was the first country to evacuate its citizens from the diamond princess, many American passengers remained angry about the experience.

US Passenger Matthew Smith tweeted: "The US government wants to take us without testing, fly us back to the US with a bunch of untested people and then quarantine us for another two weeks? What's the point?"according to twitter, smith chose to stay, rather than join the others on a chartered plane to the airbase to continue the quarantine.

In addition to the passengers on the cruise ship, public health experts have also questioned the Japanese government's policy of isolating the entire crew. "I don't understand why passengers are trapped on ships, " says Peter Hotez of the Baylor College of Medicine. "I think [ they ] used 14th-century methods and ethics to treat infectious disease patients. "

Following the successful evacuation of American passengers, Canada, Australia and India have also decided to send a special plane from the "Diamond Princess" evacuation of their citizens.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The family of Aun Na Tan, an Australian citizen trapped on board the Diamond Princess. Source: SBS

Australian Prime Minister Morrison has announced plans to send more than 200 Australian citizens from the ship, called Qantas, to Darwin, where they will be held in mandatory quarantine for 14 days. "Now I understand that the people on board and their families are very upset, " Morrison said, but stressed that protecting the health and safety of Australian citizens was a top priority.

Australia's National Security Council is understood to have taken advice from the chief health officer, Professor Murphy, before deciding to provide assistance to those on board. As of July 16, a total of 24 Australian citizens had been confirmed to have new crown pneumonia.

The 16th, "In view of the special circumstances faced by Canadian citizens aboard the Diamond Princess, we are taking action to evacuate Canadians from Japan while ensuring that appropriate measures are taken to prevent and limit the spread of COVID-19, " Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada said in a statement

As is the policy in the United States and Australia, Canadian passengers who have been diagnosed with new crown pneumonia or who show symptoms of new crown pneumonia during screening will receive treatment in Japan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Images of the Scanning electron microscope cells (pink, blue) and new coronavirus (yellow) released by the National Allergy and Institute of Medical Science. Source: NIAID

On the virus front, the Institute of Medical Science, part of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) , released electron microscopic images of the COVID-19 on Wednesday.

The coronavirus is spherical or oval in shape under an electron microscope and has regularly arranged projections that resemble a crown, giving it its name, Niaid said. The name Corona comes from the Latin word for "crown. ".

So far, scientists in the United States say they know little about the virus's properties, though the COVID-19 images are getting clearer. NIAID director Fossey said in an interview on the 16th, in terms of the cyclical nature of the flu virus, it is very reasonable to assume that warmer weather will slow down the epidemic. But for now, Fossey says, scientists have no idea what will happen after COVID-19.

Fossey also stressed that the successful development and production of a vaccine for NCP in a year was the shortest possible time, and could not be shorter. Claims that a vaccine can be developed and produced in a shorter time are shortchanging and cutting corners.

"I think we all need to be aware of the seriousness of the COVID-19 threat, " secretary of State Pompeo said at a news conference on Sunday in response to the public safety challenge posed by the new crown pneumonia, the United States will do "whatever it takes" to reduce the public risk of new pneumonia.
